d) The five-year accident history;



There have been no accidental releases from an RMP covered process in the past 5 years.    



e) The emergency response plan;



Southern Ionics Incorporated is part of the LaPorte, TX LEPC community.  The current emergency response plan for notifying the community includes an E-Notify / CAER line procedure using a 911 service for chemical spills / releases.  Shelter in-place and evacuation notification is part of this communication procedure.  The site will maintain designated employees as Hazardous Material Technicians so that responses to accidental releases to stop the release can occur.  The site will also coordinate emergency response procedures with the LEPC and conduct required drills as required under EPA requirements.  



f) Planned changes to improve safety;



For the addition of Process 2 - storage of anhydrous ammonia and manufacturing of ammonium hydroxide, ammonia detectors are being installed around the storage and manufacturing unit in the event of a release.  Per TCEQ air permit; olfactory, visual, and hearing checks of the process area are required every 4 hours.  Emergency response onsite will include Hazardous Material Technician level who can respond in order to stop a leak and to perform rescue services.  The site is part of community response plan with the LaPorte, TX LEPC.
